WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Behold, Cat Hicks, a scholar of the mind,

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
who guides the hearts of those who build with code.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Defenders of the ones mismeasured,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
she has forged the tools by which new growth is shown.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
She authored frameworks, dev thriving, AI skill and more,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
and leads as Pluralsight's keen research voice.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.000
She founded labs where open science thrives

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
to prove how teams can innovate with care.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
With Catharsis Consulting's guiding hand,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
she weds the strength of science to the heart.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Her doctorate from San Diego's halls

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000
now shapes the way that humans build with tech.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
On councils, boards, and soon in books to come,

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
she teaches how our engineering teams can grow and last.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Please join me in welcoming Cat Hicks.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Hello, folks. How wonderful to be here with you today.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.000
All right, so this is what happens

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
if you let a psychologist into your tech conference.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
I want you to take every little piece of anxiety.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
I mean, really, like, move your body.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:17.000
I'm not seeing enough.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Like, take it, bundle it up, right?

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Okay, good, we're getting there.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Take the imposter syndrome.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Take all of the little thoughts that you've had,

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
like, I need to be this, or maybe I'm not good enough at that,

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
or I'm not technical, or whatever it is.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Take that ball.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
I want you to pull it out of yourself.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Okay, good, good work.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
All right, okay, there's a beautiful little bag.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
It's right at your feet.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Take that ball.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
Just gently put it in the bag, all right?

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.000
All right, okay, good.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
You're going to regret it if you don't do it.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Okay, good, I see people doing it.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
All right, it's there if you need it, okay?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Those worries, if you want to walk out of the room,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.000
they're all there, but for this hour, we don't need it, okay?

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
All right, thank you.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Now I want us to do just another little exercise.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
It's been a couple days of being in our heads,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:18.000
so let's use our bodies more, a little embodied cognition.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Everybody who was born between January and June,

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I want you to raise your hand.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Raise your hand.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Okay, wonderful.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Now put your hand in front of your eyes.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:29.000
That's right.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Now you're not going to look for this next part.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Okay, everybody else?

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
All right, we're going to learn something.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Now your job is to keep the people with their eyes closed safe, okay?

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So don't hit anybody.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
What we're going to do is I'm going to teach you something silently.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
You're going to learn it,

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.000
and then you're going to teach it to the people who aren't looking, okay?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:53.000
Ready?

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.000
We can do it.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Okay, this is what we're going to learn.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:02.000
Okay, now you do it with me.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Ready?

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Yes.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Yes, wonderful.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Okay, I'll do it just to this side of the room.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Ready?

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
This is looking really good, you guys.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Not every audience gets this.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Okay, ready?

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:20.000
This side, this side.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Okay, all right.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
January through June, you can look now.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Okay, the half of the room that learned the secret dance,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
teach the people who didn't learn it.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.000
I'm not going to do it.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Ready?

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Let's go.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Silently.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Yes, I know you can do it.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Wonderful.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
One more run through.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Wonderful.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.000
What an audience.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Wow.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.000
My slides are also gone, by the way.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Okay, wonderful.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Everybody look at me.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
I want to see this whole audience do it.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:00.000
I'm going to check your work.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Let's go.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Wow.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
This is the most accurate audience I've ever seen do this.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:09.000
Wonderful.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So you're thinking, Kat, what on earth was that?

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
We are social learners.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And this might feel like a really silly demonstration,

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
but it is actually something that you are incredible at.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Human beings are incredible imitators.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:30.000
We can learn from other people readily.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
We do it pretty much immediately in our development.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
And the other thing, the other side of the social learning coin,

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
is we are really good at transmitting that knowledge.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
So I like to start with this kind of example,

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
because I know in technology we like to think of ourselves as inventors.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
But from the perspective of cognitive science and psychology,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:56.000
it might be more accurate to say we are really good imitators.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.000
But we are flexibly creative imitators.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So, you know, if you've ever seen a toddler with an iPad,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
you know that human beings are incredible

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
at mimicking the behaviors of other people

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.000
and using those behaviors to interact with novel objects.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Our minds can do that because we are incredibly skilled

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
at watching other people and learning from them.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
In fact, social scientists believe this capacity for imitative learning,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
this social learning, propels human culture.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:32.000
This sort of learning and teaching cycle transmits innovations,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:33.000
and we build on them,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
and that is kind of what creates what we call cumulative culture.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.000
And you can watch this unfold in technology.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
So a great example that I'd love to share

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
comes from a project that used a data set from MathWorks.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.000
They hosted 14 years of programming competitions.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Something really, really neat about the availability of data like this

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:01.000
that we have now is that you can start to watch people's solutions

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
get shared in real time, copied by others, and modified.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
This is something that there was a lot of speculation about decades ago

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
when we were talking about how people write code,

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:13.000
but we can actually see it in data sets like this.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
And indeed, they, in analyzing this data, these researchers discovered

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
it really did look like the cumulative culture patterns

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
that we might imagine from social learning.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.000
So across, I think it was more than 21 million lines of code,

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
14 years, 19 different contests,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
they found these discernible patterns.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
And these might feel really accurate to your life, your career.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
So think about it with me.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
Successful code gets copied immediately, right?

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
We can recognize other people's success, and we want to put it into practice.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:56.000
Then, solutions that are successful actually get improved

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
in this sort of group-level process.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:06:59.000
There's a cool word for this.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
We like to call it cultural ratcheting.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Picture a ratchet that tightens something.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So people can adapt those solutions to a specific context.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
They get refined over time, and it's sort of a group-level phenomenon.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
Sometimes every individual doesn't actually realize that's what they're doing,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
but it's happening anyway, which is so beautiful and cool.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
We see tweaks.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Some people are doing little tweaks on the solutions, and we see leaps forward.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Now, I think a lot of our discourse about technology focuses on the leaps,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.000
but it's important to notice both things are valuable, both things are needed.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And also, most of the leaps fail.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:46.000
So most times somebody tries to approach a problem in a completely novel way,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
it doesn't work.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
But when it does work, it works really big.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
It means big payoffs.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.000
That last one is often where we center in our thinking about innovation.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
We think, God, I want that breakthrough.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:06.000
But again, I want to bring to your attention all of this stuff is part of the same process.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
I was really, really interested in how cumulative cultures show up in technology work.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And with all of this knowledge from psychology in my back pocket,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
when I started working with software teams,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:26.000
I wasn't surprised at all to see that these social learning patterns go way beyond programming contests

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
or in-the-lab studies.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So I teamed up with an expert practitioner, my friend Ana Hevesi.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
Ana was an original community manager for Stack Overflow,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
a little website you may have heard of.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And one of my favorite things to do as a scientist is to take everything I know from the lab

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
and try to pair up with the people who have really lived it.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
And together we kind of test it all, right?

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:53.000
We say, am I right over here?

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
Have I abstracted away the realness?

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Or does this validate what you really experience?

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So we wrote a paper on this, which you can send to your boss right now.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And it's essentially our joint mission statement that says, you know,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:14.000
if you look at the real case studies, the real community phenomena across technology,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
you also see the critical role that social learning plays.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:26.000
You see breakthroughs that do not have social learning included fail, have much more friction.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:33.000
We look at things like the experience that people have with on-ramps or not having on-ramps on Stack Overflow.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And we look at technical shifts that push folks forward.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And essentially I wanted to shine a light on this underappreciated,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
but I think essential building block for technology,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
which is the fact that our problem solving is really communal.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
A very communal thing happened to me after I posted this paper.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
It's like a little preprint, and it's really nerdy.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:02.000
But at this point, nearly 7,000 folks have viewed it and sent it around to their workplaces.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And I started getting these emails from engineers, including some of the original engineers at Stack Overflow,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
which was really cool for me, who said, thank you.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:14.000
This does match my lived experience.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So I'm seeing some lovely nods.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
I'm seeing some yes energy, right?

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:24.000
This is all going super well, and I'm going to mess it up for us.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:38.000
So if all of this is happening, why do we also see really disturbing signals about how technologists feel in their day-to-day work lives?

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:43.000
If we know the importance of social learning, are they feeling like that importance is being seen?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
What you're looking at here is data I collected in a research study.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.000
These are 465 engineering managers.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:55.000
And I run a scale that I really like that I developed called the Visibility and Value Scale.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So we ask folks, do you think that technical effort—not outcomes, right, which is really important—technical effort is seen in your organization?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:06.000
Is it valued?

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And as you can see, the majority of managers say yes, 88%.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
In this study, it's between 88% and 92% every time I ask this.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Absolutely.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.000
This is an important part of my job.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Some managers wrote in in this study to describe just how much this was an important part of their job to them.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:36.000
But when you ask the people who report to those managers, only about 24% of their developers agree.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:50.000
So in these technical organizations—I'm not the only person who has measured this—we find deep misalignment between the leadership and between whether the folks on the ground and the folks doing the work feel understood.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:51.000
We see other signals.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:57.000
So leading researchers have kind of sounded an alarm for the experience of technologists.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:14.000
Greg Walton, who's a leading psychologist studying achievement and interventions, wrote a paper where they wrote, you know, folks who feel different in engineering, who feel like they don't match the norm, experience a chilly climate in which they feel unwelcome.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:31.000
Daniel Russo, a computer science professor, software researcher who studies resilience and technical teams, has written, in the midst of a rapidly changing global landscape, the profound impact of a developer's well-being on their productivity has become glaringly evident.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Margaret Ann Story, also an influential software researcher at the University of Victoria, writes, in software engineering, instances of disruptive technologies are frequent.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
So they're speaking of software engineering specifically.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
That's kind of the focus of my work.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.000
I would extend this to all of you, to everyone who's really in a knowledge work field.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:57.000
We have this fragility that's happening to the human side of technology work.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
At the same time, the complexity of that work is increasing.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
There are these disruption events happening.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
This is a tough recipe.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And I hear about this tough recipe and its impacts all the time.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So these are quotes from real developers in research interviews I conducted.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:20.000
One engineer told me, so much of my work just never sees the light of day.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Someone said, we're building castles in our minds, and sometimes you wake up to an email that just demolishes something you were building for years.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:36.000
And another person put it really bluntly, I'm not convinced our leadership thinks we're people.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Yeah, that one always gets a sad laugh.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
I'm familiar with this sad laugh.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
I find this really, really poignant.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
And it really provoked a dilemma for me as a psychologist.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Something like this question kept coming to my heart.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:02.000
How is it that we all can be producing this work that our world depends on, but it feels so hard for it to get seen?

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
It feels so hard to be seen as humans.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
I want you to also think about this conference right now.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And how many times have you gone to a community like this and then gone back to your workplace with big plans, big inspirations, and sort of hit a brick wall?

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:25.000
It's really hard to have a good culture as a technology person, right?

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
As a data scientist, as a developer.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And this is what I want to center the rest of our time around.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
Why is this so hard and what can we do about it?

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:41.000
In particular, what's the psychology behind some of the reasons we end up with maladaptive strategies?

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:48.000
So I'm going to give you like a really, you know, 30,000 foot flyover view of some of my work.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
All of this work is pretty much available to you.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And I also love talking about this more to teams.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:01.000
So treat this as like a little window into the psychology of technical teams into which you can go deeper.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And again, you know, send to your boss, maybe.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
All right.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:11.000
I started working with technology teams by doing a learning science project.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And this was such a fun and ridiculous thing that I did.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:22.000
I decided I was going to do a research study completely for free on my own, self-funded, when I was living in San Francisco.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And I wanted it to be about developers learning.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
See, I had come into tech with a learning science background.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:33.000
And I was really curious what learning looked like on these technical teams.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So I started with a qualitative study where I interviewed 25 developers about their problem solving and their learning.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:42.000
And I did a couple of things.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
I had them sit down with me.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:51.000
I sat across from them so I couldn't see their code, right, and actually work in front of me and do this thing that we call talk out loud.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:58.000
Which is a really fun exercise where you get people to sort of describe the decisions they're making as they're working.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:05.000
I focused on whether when people were solving bugs in their work and when they were ramping up into a new code base.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
Which is a really interesting psychological moment for people.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And then I did follow-up interviews where I asked them a ton of questions.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:18.000
Like every piece of data I'm going to mention in this talk, this is available for you to go read much more in depth.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:28.000
But the big takeaway that I came out of this study with was that developers are feeling this deep tension when it came to their learning needs.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.000
I named this tension learning debt, like technical debt.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:38.000
Learning debt is this thing that is accruing, like a damaging cycle for tech teams.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And it functions something like this.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:49.000
Developers go into their code writers, knowledge work people, they go into their work and they know that they need to do active learning.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:57.000
But if they are in an environment that discourages sharing that learning or having that be an open part of your job.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Then they're kind of getting these messages all throughout that there's no support for you.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:05.000
They go into other processes.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
I pulled up code review here as an example.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But all of the kinds of moments where they interact with their teams were brought up in these interviews.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And in those kind of code reviews, sometimes a very important thing would happen.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Which is that they would get a really snide negative message about learning.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:34.000
So for example, maybe a senior engineer would say, you know, I'm not interested in like the things you tried that didn't work or don't bother me.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.000
A manager would say, you know, I can't adjust the timeline for you.

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
Like learn on the evenings and the weekends.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Those kinds of messages that essentially sent people back to their environment with the idea that it is not OK to show that I need to learn here.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
I still need to learn, but I cannot let on to other people that that's happening.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
That is learning debt, right?

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:57.000
That tension that's happening.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:07.000
This is just one way that I see bad psychology kind of creeping in and starting to chip away at our well-being.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
And this disturbed me a lot as a learning scientist.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
So I decided to go deeper.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:18.000
And the place where I went is an idea that I really love called psychological affordances.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.000
I started to suspect that to really understand and fix this type of pattern on teams.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.000
And I started to consult with engineering teams as well.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
So I was putting this into practice myself.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:35.000
We need to learn about the psychological affordances that our environments are giving technical people.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
So what's a psychological affordance?

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:41.000
Well, this is the picture of me kayaking off the coast of Kauai.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:47.000
And I never could have had this experience without the affordances that a kayak gave me.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:47.000


00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
I can't swim that well or that far.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:59.000
But with the extension of the kayak, with the rowing, with everything that we had access to, I had these design affordances, right?

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
They expanded my capacities.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Social scientists also think about affordances.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:13.000
We think about the messages that are around people and what people get that defines what they think is possible for them.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:18.000
That process of kind of making that decision looks something like this.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:26.000
In our environments, you can think of this working almost like a little scientific theory that you carry around with you.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:31.000
You might ask yourself, what does it mean to be a productive technologist here?

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:35.000
Productive, successful developer in this place.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:38.000
And then we go out into our environments and we experiment.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
We conduct small, little experiments.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:44.000
We take the results of those as the answer to our questions.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:48.000
We do this all the time without even necessarily thinking about it.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:51.000
And then we calibrate our behaviors.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
This is how cultures get formed.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:59.000
And it's also how we set ourselves off onto certain adaptive or less adaptive paths.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:08.000
Wanting to understand this cycle and how I could help people with it is one of the really big reasons that I became a psychologist.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.000
And even though this cycle presents us with some challenges, it also has a lot of hope in it.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:19.000
Because if we didn't have this kind of ongoing experimental cycle all the time, we could never change a culture that we're in.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:24.000
We are all as individuals creating the cultures that we're in all the time.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:29.000
So if we can intervene on parts of this cycle, that is our path to change.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:40.000
But what answer to that question are we getting from the stereotypes that our cultures, societies, and workplaces hold about technical work?

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:46.000
I really had to figure this out before I could figure out how to help these tech teams.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
And I have proposed an answer for you.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:56.000
I think that we are getting really bad psychology answers about technology work.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:09.000
One of the things that we know in social science is that when we as people don't have really clear, shared beliefs about how things work, we tend to default to deeply held stereotypes.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:15.000
And I think that I see these experiences and measure these in my research all the time.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:18.000
I have a name for it so that you can remember it.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.000
I call this the brains in jars model of software development.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:27.000
My empirical research primarily focuses on beliefs about software development.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:31.000
But I would invite you to consider how this might have leaked into your fields, right?

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:34.000
Because these are kind of pervasive stereotypes.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So what is the brains in jars model?

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:47.000
Picture those little jars in a sci-fi scene, right, where there's a detached pink brain and it's floating in jelly.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And haven't you ever felt like that is how my boss thinks about me, right?

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:57.000
So in this model, technical people are isolated individuals.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:58.000
They are just brains.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:01.000
So we only care about their cognition.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
We don't like feelings.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
We don't like mushy stuff.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:14.000
Psychological safety maybe we think is a cute buzzword that's like a nice to have, but it doesn't really have anything to do with technical problem solving.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:19.000
In fact, it actually might be opposed to technical problem solving in a lot of people's minds.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:25.000
Brains in jars models do not have to define like an entire organization.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:30.000
I think of it more as like a set of stereotypes that can get activated for people.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:37.000
Now, there are three thinking traps that I look for as a psychologist when I work with engineering orgs.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:43.000
And when I see these traps, I think I've got a little bit of a brains in jars vibe going on here.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
OK, so I'll give you these three thinking traps.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.000
Watch for these.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:52.000
The first one is you will see your organization fall into what I call brittle productivity.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:23:01.000
This is when we start to believe that the only way to produce the outcomes we want is the grind, the cramming all night.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
Nobody can actually do that.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
I'm sorry to break it to you.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
So what starts to happen is that people posture.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
They pretend that they can do that.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:13.000
You see it start to become about the performance of productivity.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
We pursue short term cycles of extremely hard effort.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
We disguise the breakdown.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:26.000
And ultimately, this is a really dangerous place for organizations because it looks kind of good.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:34.000
For kind of a long time, actually, because technical people are capable of doing this posturing in an overachieving sort of way.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:41.000
But sometimes I tell leaders when they're consulting with me, I would prefer that we just saw your org look dysfunctional.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:45.000
Because I don't like it when you are all hitting your targets and people are burning out.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:46.000
That's really dangerous.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
It's difficult for you to detect.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.000
I had an engineer friend one time who announced to me.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:54.000
I know that I am a technical mind.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:59.000
I know that I was meant for this work because every day at every night at 3 a.m.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:03.000
I like jolt awake and I'm thinking about solving technical problems.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:06.000
This is clearly the only thing my brain wants to do.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:08.000
And I said, I'm sorry, babe.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:12.000
That's anxious rumination and it's not good.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.000
All right.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:17.000
The second thinking trap is called the chilly climate trap.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:24.000
So have you ever been in a tech place where it just feels kind of like you have to be cold?

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.000
You're sort of supposed to hold back emotions all the time.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:38.000
You know, our bosses and colleagues maybe have this stereotype that, you know, the more efficient you are, the less you are emoting, the more technical you are.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.000
And it's kind of like a pervasive culture.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
It's hard to name because it's a really big thing.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
But people have called it a chilly climate.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:54.000
My friend Titus Winters, who helps drive DevEx at Adobe and wrote the book Software Engineering at Google, recently gave a keynote.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:56.000
Great keynote at the C++ meeting.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:57.000
Highly recommend.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And the whole keynote was about fear.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Titus has led some of the greatest technical teams in the world and proposes that fear is one of the biggest challenges that we are facing in tech right now.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.000
And it's something critical for us to understand.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:20.000
Fear about using technical systems, inherent fear of doing cutting edge work, of the risk involved.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:24.000
I think this is kind of a shadow behind a lot of us.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:25.000
All right.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:32.000
The third thinking trap that marks Brains and Jars Organizations is probably my favorite one to beat up online.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.000
This is the lone genius trap.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:40.000
In this thinking trap, we say tech excellence is the exclusive provenance of a gifted few.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.000
A great example of this might be the 10X engineer or the 10X developer.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:52.000
If you've ever heard this kind of idea, that there are some individuals in technology who just dramatically outpace other ones.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:56.000
I've heard people talk about 10X data scientists as well.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And the kind of thinking goes like, if those outliers are the people who really outproduce, then those are the ones who drive our real outcomes.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
Those are the only ones we should really care about and protect.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:12.000
Anything they do is fine because we're getting that 10X output from them.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:13.000
Okay.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:16.000
These are some difficult beliefs I've just laid down.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:20.000
All I want from you right now is to just remember these three traps.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:24.000
We are going to be putting them to the empirical test.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:32.000
But first, I want to tell you what psychology thinks, a different perspective about you and your work.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:45.000
When I founded the Dev Success Lab and gathered together a scrappy, interdisciplinary, very small little lab to specifically study technical teams, we decided to do a big lit review on what we should focus on.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
And this is what we came up with.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:57.000
These four factors, which I have spent a lot of my time working on, stand in great contrast to the brains in jars model.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:09.000
When I look at the psychological affordances that seem to unlock outcomes in a sustainable way over people's whole lifetimes, we end up on experiences like this.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:22.000
We have learning culture, which is the experience of learning being celebrated, shared in your environment, seen as a good, productive, normal part of your life and of being a competent person.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
We have sense of agency.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:31.000
Agency is like this fundamental belief we have that when we do something, a result will happen.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.000
Imagine times that you have had something come in the middle of that connection.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:38.000
It's very disempowering, very frightening for people.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
We have self-advocacy and motivation.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:49.000
We think of self-advocacy and psychology as kind of like this psychological engine, this powerhouse that keeps you going over friction.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:28:02.000
So self-advocacy is like this positive belief that even if an unexpected thing comes to me and I don't know how to solve it and I'm feeling the intensity of that, you can say to yourself, I know I can do this.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
I believe in myself.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
You have this kind of core.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:12.000
Sense of belonging, finally, is one of my favorite, favorite psychological measures.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:19.000
We can capture this kind of big construct around, do I truly believe I belong here?

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.000
So that cycle of question asking, I ask, do I belong in this?

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:26.000
Does someone like me belong in this environment?

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:29.000
The answer more often than not comes back as yes.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Then you have a high sense of belonging.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:41.000
All of these outcomes, all four of them, important to me, have been tested in a lot of empirical research outside of research on tech teams.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:45.000
There wasn't a lot to go on on the psychology of tech teams.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:57.000
So we looked to psychologists who had studied what helps students succeed, what helps doctors navigate stress, what helps pilots, what helps everybody who's doing difficult decision making.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:01.000
And we decided to go out and test this idea.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:08.000
So we recruited about 1,282 technologists into an open science project.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:14.000
And we bundled these factors into something that we call the LABS model.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:18.000
My team told me I had to make it an acronym so that somebody in tech would remember it.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:20.000
So you can remember that.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:28.000
And we measured developers' self-reported productivity and found a persistent, statistically significant association.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
This is just a simple visualization of that.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:34.000
You can check out our paper for all of the models.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:43.000
And we are not the only people who have found this, that those teams in those better environments win out on productivity.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:49.000
Lots of software research that we cite in our report also underlies this connection.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:53.000
We find that this works across a lot of diverse contexts.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:30:00.000
So something I'm really proud of in this project is that we did not just stick with your hundred friends at Microsoft.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.000
No offense to them.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
But we recruited across the world.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
We recruited across more than 12 industries.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
We looked at this connection across many, many demographics.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:21.000
And we found that when you have what we call developer thriving, these four factors, it's a pretty good signal for being in a place where you can be a more productive person.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
All right.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
So we've observed this connection in the world.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:34.000
I wanted to learn a lot more about what can start to help us when we are stuck in those brains in jars cycles.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:41.000
And one inspiration I took from this was a conversation that I had, a really deep, ongoing conversation with a friend of mine.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:46.000
This is not his real name, but he volunteered his story for this.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.000
So we'll call him Sean.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.000
My friend Sean was a really high achiever his whole life.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:54.000
He discovered coding in high school.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
Loved it.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
Excelled through college.

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:00.000
Felt like he was living the dream.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
He also said he was living his parents' dream.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:07.000
Got a very high-paying developer job at a top tech company.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
And he was just flying.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
He loved coding.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
He loved the puzzles of programming.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:16.000
He hit all of his goals.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:17.000
Promotion, promotion.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
He got his staff promotion, which he was really excited about.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:25.000
And then he woke up like a cloud had come over him.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Like where the motivation that he used to feel was just gone.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
It wasn't there anymore.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
And I like to tell people I am a lab psychologist.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.000
I'm not a couch psychologist.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:43.000
But my friends do still sometimes come to me to say, Kat, something is happening to me.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:44.000
Can you help me understand it?

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:46.000
What is it?

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:50.000
I can't answer everything about what's happening inside of people's heads.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:57.000
But I sat down with my friend Sean and I said, well, like what do you think makes you feel motivated?

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:06.000
Sean started to realize there was this big tension he had felt his whole life between having goals of performing.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.000
Like demonstrating his competence and how excellent he was in front of people.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
And goals of mastery.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:23.000
This matches on to two kind of dueling concepts that psychologists who study people's beliefs in school and achievement have found.

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:27.000
We can divide people into kind of these two camps a lot of the time.

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:32.000
Sean had really fallen into this performance camp his whole life and it served him well.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.000
He wanted to get the promotion.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:35.000
He wanted to get the A's.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
He wanted his parents to be proud of him.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:40.000
All of these are very worthy survival goals.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:47.000
However, the thing that motivated Sean, the thing that motivates a lot of us, tends to fall in the mastery camp.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:52.000
Mastery is when we are seeking learning for its own sake.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:33:02.000
So when you think about, if you ever heard the word intrinsic motivation, what is intrinsic about it is that the doing the thing itself becomes kind of the goal.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:05.000
So you're rewarded for it immediately.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
The journey is the destination.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:14.000
All of those beautiful sort of Zen things that people say actually have a deep grain of psychological truth to it.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:19.000
Because that is a much more sustainable source for our motivation.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
Now something interesting happens if you get unbalanced between these two things.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:26.000
And I think this is what was happening for my friend Sean.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:32.000
He started to get so locked in on the performance goals when he became a staff engineer.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:40.000
He felt in his mind, it wasn't even really a conscious thought, but he thought, I can never mess up in front of my team again.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:44.000
This is what we call in psychology an avoidance strategy.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
It feels great.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
It does not work.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:56.000
So the more you say, OK, I'm going to achieve my performance goal by never putting myself in a position where I could make a mistake.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:59.000
So you stop going to the optional team meetings.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
You stop mentoring people.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
You actually stop doing the things that grow your skills.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.000
You don't get those small failures on the way to the big leaps that we talked about.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:10.000
Right.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:15.000
You are boxing yourself in and you're going to become a lower performer at the end of the day.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:16.000
Right.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:18.000
This is kind of a big paradox.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:24.000
I actually described it to my friend Sean as what I call the performance paradox.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Because we know a lot about why this happens.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
We can explore it from many angles.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:36.000
So, for instance, like in our cognition, we are pretty bad evaluators of our in the moment performance.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:40.000
We tend to think that performance is the same thing as learning.

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:43.000
But famously, it is really not.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:49.000
Actually, you want to see people make a lot of mistakes, kind of get worse on the path to getting better.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
That is normal, sustainable learning.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:55.000
We also can explore this across people's careers.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:05.000
So the more you see people fixate on demonstrating explicit performance, the more you see that they get really fragile under pressure.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:10.000
So that's kind of like that high achieving kid who can't tolerate getting a low grade.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:13.000
The first time they get it, they sort of lose all their strategies.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:14.000
Right.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
You don't want to be like that person.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:20.000
And this is damaging on the scale of our communities.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:26.000
So psychologists have measured the beliefs that an entire field or a community might have.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:38.000
And they find that the more of professional field or a discipline in the world focuses on this kind of performance, focuses on brilliance, which we'll dive more into in a second.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:42.000
The less that sets that field up for success.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:48.000
The field gets worse at recognizing people who actually have high potential and it gets more fragile.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.000
So the performance paradox.

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
I want to give you just a couple little handles.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:56.000
If this is I've seen some like sad faces.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:57.000
All right.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
And I want to tell you this is OK.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:04.000
This is like a normal part of being a hardworking person.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:09.000
The key is to think about your mindset and think about your context.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:13.000
And you can, like my friend Sean, take action on this.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:19.000
So we had a couple moments, coffee chats where we sat down by the end of these chats.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:26.000
Sean had challenged himself to start doing mentoring with his team again to show some vulnerability in front of them.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:34.000
And he went from being a person who really was hiding out, not having any connection at work, to being essentially like the learning leader on his team.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
And he was way happier.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:44.000
The way I think about breaking down these dilemmas is this handy metaphor that I really like from Walton and Yeager called the seed in the soil metaphor.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:51.000
This helps us think about what psychologists call the mindset of the individual, but also the context of the environment.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:58.000
So you can think about the soil as kind of the adaptive social context that we need.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:04.000
That affords us the opportunity to put our good beliefs into practice.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:07.000
That hypothesis testing that we were talking about.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
But we also need good seeds.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:13.000
So you as an individual might be working on the seed part.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:19.000
These are our adaptive psychological beliefs that create kind of more resilient behavior goals.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:23.000
So focusing more on mastery might be this good seed.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:27.000
But then you also need a really beautiful strong soil.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:37.000
Like if you have a boss who hates the fact that you're trying to focus on a mastery goal, that is going to really foreclose on how much you can exercise that belief.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:41.000
Leaders in the room, your job is soil.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Individual contributors, your future leaders.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.000
So think about the soil, but your job is the seed.

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
That's what I would say about that.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:54.000
If you need something stronger to hit your organization over the head with, I have created a law.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:58.000
People love to create really silly laws in software.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
So I decided I needed one.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:01.000
This is Kat's law.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:14.000
The more a software team focuses on demonstrating short-term performance in their environment, the less they are able to protect the foundation on which long-term performance depends.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:15.000
All right.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:19.000
Feel free to spread this everywhere.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:20.000
OK.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:27.000
So we have learned a lot now about how in general really good psychology leads to better productivity.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:32.000
We have evidence against that brains in jars stereotype about you as technical people.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:37.000
But I want to talk about situations that turn up the dial of pressure.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:38.000
Right.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:43.000
Because a lot of times I get this kind of feedback when I'm talking to especially engineering leaders.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:44.000
OK, Kat.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:45.000
All right.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:46.000
This sounds great.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:52.000
We will work on it when nothing is happening and everything is great, which is never right.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:56.000
So folks say this sounds nice, but my team's under pressure.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
We have to deliver.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
We have to go to burnout strategies.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:01.000
Right.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:02.000
So.

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:03.000
All right.

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:04.000
I'm an empiricist.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:05.000
I said, let's test it.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:08.000
We know something about stress in psychology.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:12.000
I think of these as threat experiences.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:20.000
When you are experiencing a moment of threat as a person, questions might be coming up for you like, am I going to lose something?

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.000
Am I going to be evaluated unfairly?

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:27.000
Other kinds of questions that tap into those core psychological affordances like agency.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:28.000
Right.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:29.000
Am I going to lose control?

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
Will I have a choice in those moments?

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:37.000
Threat puts us in like a different state because it really is a moment where our priorities shift.

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
We're trying to protect ourselves.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.000
We're trying to survive.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.000
And I know it's easy to think about this if you're about to be hit by a car.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:45.000
Right.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:50.000
But if you deeply value technical work, you can also be in a state of threat about it.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:51.000
Right.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:54.000
If you think someone's going to take something away from you.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:58.000
Also, throughout our lives, we are always adapting our beliefs.

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:03.000
We're always doing what what we call contextual sense making.

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:12.000
So even though you maybe learn to be the person in tech and you have the title and you have, you know, it's actually not as fixed as our organizations make it out to be.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:15.000
Right. You're always asking, well, what does it mean now?

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
What does it mean this quarter?

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:18.000
Right.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:24.000
But perhaps a moment in tech is coming up to you in terms of threat, in terms of sense making.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:27.000
And that moment is probably AI.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:28.000
Right.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:33.000
My research lab decided we had to study AI.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:39.000
I really was a bit reluctant to do it because it felt like such a loaded experience.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:47.000
The first thing I thought of when I started listening to how technical people were talking about AI was this experience of threat.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:52.000
So we decided to tackle this in a project we named the new developer.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:56.000
And what we wanted to do was focus on the human.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:05.000
In particular, what human environments help technical people thrive when they are grappling with the changes that might be introduced by AI.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:08.000
So we needed a couple tools in our arsenal to do this.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:17.000
Remember, I told you we were like a scrappy multidisciplinary team inventing new methods that did not really exist for these kinds of questions.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:18.000
So we did a few things.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:21.000
We knew we needed to recruit real teams.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
There's a lot of sandboxing going on around AI.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
A lot of kind of let's bring my five friends into the lab.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:29.000
We wanted to get into the real world.

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:33.000
We wanted to watch teams that were doing real AI adoption.

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:34.000
Right.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:37.000
Not the hype, but actually pulling those tools in.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:38.000
We knew to do this.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:40.000
We needed to recruit inclusively.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
We needed to analyze intersectionally.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
This was a really big deal to me.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:51.000
I don't know if you consume these large surveys like the Stack Overflow survey or initiatives like that.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:42:04.000
As a research leader and a social scientist, I had always noticed that their representation of women hovered around 3 or 4 percent, which does not reflect the demographics of technical organizations.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:07.000
We attempted to reflect those demographics.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:10.000
We achieved over 30 percent women in this study.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.000
And that took a lot of me posting in forums.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:16.000
We also needed to develop new measures.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
We have released those publicly.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:23.000
So you can take this also to your boss and say let's measure these things.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:24.000
Right.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
And we pre-registered all of these questions.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.000
You can explore that.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:33.000
You can see that some of my hypotheses in this study, in fact, were not met, which is also really interesting.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:41.000
But the ones that were, we hypothesized that we would find AI skill threat, what I've named AI skill threat.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:57.000
This is a pervasive feeling of stress, anxiety, fear being in that threat state when we ask people to imagine generative AI as changing their job, changing the future of technical work.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
These are a couple ways you can measure it.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:09.000
As you can see, about half of the people, it's like 43 to 45 percent, depending on which questions you're bundling here, folks show up with this AI skill threat.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
So it's really pretty pervasive.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:12.000
Right.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:19.000
So we wanted to ask, what is it that seems to raise or lower the temperature on AI skill threat?

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:23.000
We had two very strong educated hunches.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:27.000
We like to glorify these as scientists by calling them hypotheses.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:41.000
But our research-backed hunches were, one of the things that was going to raise the temperature on AI skill threat, really push it into the forefront for people, is that lone genius stereotype.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:47.000
So there's a couple ways that social scientists have looked at this type of belief, and we focused on two of them.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:43:49.000
One is something we call brilliance beliefs.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:59.000
Do you believe that ultimately the most successful software development is driven by an innate property of brilliance?

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:01.000
You need to be brilliant to be successful here.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:06.000
Now, when folks tend to believe this, they tend to do something else.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:10.000
Something that we call a technical contest.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:19.000
Have you ever been in a conversation where someone's, I don't know, I don't even know how to like, because I try not to do this in my life, so I don't actually know how to imitate it.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:24.000
But has someone ever been like, oh, you don't know that keyboard shortcut?

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:30.000
You have the wrong stickers on your laptop.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:31.000
Right.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:37.000
So we naturally kind of like try to assess people, try to sort of understand people's competence.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:51.000
But when you are in a culture that really explicitly pits people against each other, people kind of see it as their job to decide if you're good enough, if you're technical enough, which is the same thing as good in a lot of these teams.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:52.000
Right.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:57.000
We call that a technical contest culture, and it is terrible to experience.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:02.000
So these are linked because a lot of times people think only a few people can be brilliant.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:06.000
I better make sure I'm one of them, so I better win all these contests.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:11.000
You kind of end up like in this punching match all the time with everybody around you every moment.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.000
You're never safe.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:13.000
Okay.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.000
What is the contrast to this?

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:18.000
We tried again to tap into those drivers of cumulative culture.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:22.000
So we measured learning culture in particular.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
We measured belonging in particular.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:34.000
We see these beliefs strongly negatively correlate with the brilliance and the, you know, the technical contest that we thought this is a pretty good target.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:41.000
I bet that these things are going to be putting people in a different mindset about themselves and about technical work.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:44.000
And indeed, that is exactly what we found.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:51.000
So across more than 5,000 developers and their managers, across, again, an inclusive sample of more than 12 industries,

00:45:51.000 --> 00:46:00.000
we find that if you are on an environment that is much more like this lone genius culture, you are twice as likely to have AI skill threat.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:07.000
Now, it doesn't vanish completely in cumulative cultures because it's a big world and lots of things are affecting our minds, right?

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:10.000
But it significantly decreases it.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:15.000
Imagine, like, a drug that cuts, you know, your rates in half like this.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.000
We find this to be a really exciting signal.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:26.000
And we also find for those bosses who don't care about feelings, these teams are more productive.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:29.000
They say that I'm more productive as an individual.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:35.000
They also say my team as a whole is more effective, which I highly recommend, by the way,

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:41.000
if you are at an org that runs, like, DevEx or productivity studies, include this measure.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:48.000
Team effectiveness in our studies is not the same as individual productivity, and it's really fun to ask about both things.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:52.000
All right, so they win, again.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:56.000
Our lab decided we were going to get even more ambitious.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:01.000
We wanted to ask, what can we learn on the scale of software organizations?

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:12.000
Now, at this point in our research, I felt really confident that all those lone genius explanations were not an accurate way to describe how software development worked.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:15.000
But I wanted to put it to the test.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:20.000
Now, I'm excited to share this with you all because I know how much you appreciate data.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:26.000
And we were very excited to put this to an extremely datafied test.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:34.000
So imagine that 10x developer idea, right, that comes sort of in the brains of JAR's model.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:42.000
If we thought that there are a few people who are just such dramatic outliers in production, what would we expect to find?

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.000
Well, folks in software have made this argument a lot.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:47.000
They've said there are 10x developers.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
They are faster than everybody else.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:52.000
That's the primary way that it's been measured.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:57.000
My team had access to something that we call cycle time.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:03.000
So if you're at an organization that puts things into tickets, you might know this kind of beast.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:11.000
But what it essentially is is that technical folks are supposed to mark the start and the end of a cycle of work.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:19.000
And we had access to a tremendous amount of software metrics data, which you can go read, all the complexity of that.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:24.000
We know that it represents tons and tons of different kinds of work, right?

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:34.000
But we had access to this incredible sample, and we decided to ask ourselves, across all of this cycle time, can we detect these outliers?

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:38.000
Almost like an adversarial study of our own beliefs that they wouldn't be there.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:46.000
So we looked at over 55,000 cycle time data points, over 11,000 individuals, 216 organizations.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:52.000
Our lead author was John Florney, did an incredible job on this, our methodologist and statistician in my lab.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:58.000
And there's also a great GitHub repo for this paper, so you can get all the code.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:48:59.000
All right.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:00.000
What did we find?

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:03.000
Were those 10x developers present?

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:05.000
They were not.

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:11.000
At the scale of thousands of developers doing thousands of software tasks, we did not find this proof.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:16.000
What you are looking at here, because it's so much data, you know I can't visualize it.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:22.000
What you're looking at here is a visualization that takes some randomly sampled individuals in our data set.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:26.000
And I think the first thing that probably pops out is noise, right?

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:35.000
Or just variation, probably not noise, just meaningful variation that doesn't correspond to reliable, consistent individual differences.

00:49:35.000 --> 00:49:38.000
We did find some interesting effects in this study.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:41.000
They mostly probably match what you already know.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:50.000
So the effect shown here, for instance, is if you are getting a little bit more time to focus on coding in the week, your cycle times get shorter.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.000
That is represented in color here.

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:56.000
So a little bit of clustering of color above and below the line.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:02.000
But you can also probably see that's even not a great predictor for all of this variation, right?

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:13.000
We propose in our study the places that leaders need to look is not individual explanations, but organizational explanations, right?

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:21.000
We need to get clearer about types of work and stop relying on very simplistic benchmarks.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:25.000
We propose that, and I've seen a lot of orgs that I've worked with do this.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:33.000
If you take really oversimplified averages, you say, my team needs to hit this benchmark average of cycle time.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:35.000
If you're below it, you're bad.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
That is essentially bullshit.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:48.000
In fact, for even a single individual, their own past average cycle time is not a good predictor of their future average cycle time.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:50.000
This work is really hard, you all.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
It is really variable.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:55.000
It's also not good between organizations.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:58.000
So even organizations vary heavily from each other.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:04.000
This is a map of distributions of cycle time across our more than 200 organizations.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:15.000
So if you are a leader listening to this and people are telling you you need to compare to other organizations, just know that comparison might be fairly meaningless, right?

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:18.000
Your average, it might be very different from someone.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:24.000
If you don't know what drives kind of the variation that we see, then where are you going to get?

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:29.000
You can, again, check out our entire project for all of our recommendations on this.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:39.000
But at the end of the day, I felt like we were kind of just nailing the hammer into the coffin of the 10x developer idea, and that gave me a lot of joy.

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:43.000
So I think the 10x developer thing is wrong.

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:48.000
Other research you can bring to bear on this is really, really interesting that I'll point you to.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:54.000
We have a very strong meritocracy bias in especially westernized cultures.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:58.000
We like to think about individual explanations.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:03.000
The more we think about those explanations, the more cognitively accessible they are to us.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:14.000
So two people could look at the same data, and one of them is really deep in this meritocracy bias, and all that ever comes up into their mind are individual explanations.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:20.000
And they go to their next leadership meeting, and they say, well, all that's ever been in the past is individual explanations.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:23.000
So we're caught in this kind of loop of bad attributions, right?

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:27.000
I'm interested in breaking this trap for us.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:37.000
Even if you want meritocracy, if you say to your organization, I want you to please become meritocratic, it doesn't work usually.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:47.000
So there's a number of interesting studies about telling managers, we want you to become really meritocratic and assess individual performance, and that's all you're going to reward.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:50.000
And then those managers become more biased.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:53:04.000
And we think this happens because it makes people feel like they are meritocratic without actually doing the work to recognize structural, systemic biases, things that have kept them from seeing certain forms of work.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:12.000
So what is a much more healthy message is we're all living in environments, and there's some bias to what you see.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:16.000
So let's get more transparency to how we're evaluating performance.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:22.000
Let's sort of not take the I don't see color approach to bias, right?

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:31.000
And finally, if you're just a nerd about reading 1960s software papers like I am, they are bad.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:32.000
They're terrible.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:36.000
Please, I would love more data scientists to read these papers.

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:42.000
Take averages from individuals without looking at the variation in a single individual's response.

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:58.000
And that kind of statement about individual differences in human ability then gets reified and put into very influential software books, even though it was sometimes based on somebody's 12 friends in a lab in a terrible task.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:01.000
All right. So the whole 10x developer thing is wrong.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:04.000
And it's also really boring. Right.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:09.000
We can move past these 1960s style studies.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:14.000
OK. This has been a lot of evidence, but I have more evidence.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:28.000
OK. And the reason is because sometimes I present all of this stuff, all of this work we've done, and I'll have a very poignant conversation like a developer will say, Kat, this is all very observational.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:36.000
My leader doesn't believe in surveys, and I believe in what you're doing, but it's really too bad that we can't run an RCT in the real world.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:52.000
We're not scientists here, and we can't have that, like, really strong empirical evidence of an intervention to convince our bosses that investing in psychology matters, to which I said I will do that.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:58.000
So we ran an RCT in my lab, and we decided to focus on code review anxiety.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:04.000
This is led by Carol Lee, the lead author, the designer of the clinical workshop in this study.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:08.000
She's a phenomenal clinician and an anxiety expert.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:17.000
And for the few years we were running these other studies, we were saying to ourselves, you know, people are giving really bad advice about anxiety to technologists.

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:27.000
A lot of folks we talked to, like staff engineers, would say, oh, yes, folks are very anxious about code reviews, and the way to get over that is to get better at code reviews.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:30.000
And that's not how anxiety works.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:40.000
Very experienced people with lots and lots of skills can still get trapped in the kind of maladaptive, difficult psychological experience of anxiety.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:41.000
It happens all the time.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
There's nothing abnormal about it.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:45.000
It's a part of the human condition.

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:51.000
What we wanted to do in this study was show that those psychological mindsets really mattered.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:54.000
So we recruited a bunch of developers.

00:55:54.000 --> 00:56:02.000
We used a design that we call a waitlist control, where some folks are held out, so they do the pre and the post measures.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:07.000
And then they just get the intervention because we think the intervention is great and everybody should get it, right?

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:11.000
But what we compare is their pre and post without the intervention.

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:13.000
And then we have the intervention participants.

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:23.000
So we recruit folks, and those folks got a psychology workshop led by a clinical psychologist, and it did not focus on making them better at code, right?

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:37.000
What it focused on was helping them learn the skills of self-efficacy, learn the mechanism of anxiety, learn more about the cycles, how it works, and critically to focus on self-compassion.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:53.000
So to learn in the moment of like fearing being evaluated by another person that you could run through kind of a script we provided around saying, you know, I share humanity with this person, and it is okay to be human as a technologist, right?

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:01.000
Like all of those resilient sort of suit of armor things that help you resist that brains in jars dehumanization.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:03.000
So what happens?

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:06.000
It worked, all right, which is a thrill for us.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
We significantly reduced code review anxiety.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:15.000
What you're looking for here is the difference between the averages and the workshop condition on the left.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:18.000
The control condition did not see a significant change in this.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:25.000
We also improved their self-efficacy, and we increased their self-compassion.

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:33.000
Now, just a little like behind the scenes from a psychologist is that it's really hard to move people's self-compassion around.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:36.000
So we were thrilled by this.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:40.000
We also saw some very pragmatic outcomes for organizations.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:56.000
So for instance, using this psychology intervention, which we also sent people home with and tested whether it helped them in ongoing code reviews, which it did, we saw about a 40% decrease in avoidance of technical problem solving.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:07.000
So when people felt like in this really difficult psychological place, they were doing things like checking out of code reviews, putting them off, waiting until Friday to do the worst code review they've ever done.

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:12.000
You know, all of that kind of avoidance behavior, right, that we think is going to make us feel better, and it doesn't.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:16.000
We were able to reduce that by a huge amount.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:22.000
You can access this whole workbook that we created based on this study.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
You can send it around to your team.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:30.000
We've also done a lot of science communication about it, and all of this stuff is on my website.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:31.000
All right.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:36.000
To wrap up, can we break up with this brains in jars model?

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:37.000
I think that we can.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:42.000
I think that we can do it in a number of ways that I've tried to approach in my work with teams.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:47.000
We can do it by careful observation of the psychological affordances that folks really know.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:54.000
We can do it by looking at specific moments of disruption and change, looking at what environments protect that.

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:58.000
We can even test and develop actual explicit interventions.

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:02.000
If you want to do this for your organization, call me.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:11.000
And we can take advantage of the incredible data that we have in the world to understand technical teams to rewrite these old, tired stories.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:23.000
Final little hopeful point for you is that when I asked developers, technical people in my studies, whether they think that helping somebody else is a critical part of their job.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:27.000
Over 90% of them say yes.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:28.000
This is who you are.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:32.000
You are people, and I will never stop seeing you as people.

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.000
You can find my work here.

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:38.000
I have a book coming out in 2026 called The Psychology of Software Teams.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:45.000
I write a newsletter called Fight for the Human, and I consult with engineering orgs, tech teams, and anybody who needs my help.

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:47.000
Thank you so much for the time.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:59.000
Thank you for that.

00:59:59.000 --> 01:00:00.000
Thank you for that wonderful keynote.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:09.000
I think we've got time for one quick question, so let's do the most popular one, which is also very relevant to me.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:18.000
What can a team of remote employees do to really encourage social learning?

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:26.000
I think it depends on what kind of remote situation you're in, because I think that remote situations are different.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:29.000
In some ways, they turn up the dial.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.000
It's like one of those high-pressure things.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:38.000
I used to work on online learning, like MOOCs and students who were far removed from the teacher.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:45.000
One of the things that we always saw was that you are kind of in a stripped-down situation.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:55.000
You have fewer social cues to go on, so the social cues that you do get become sometimes really powerful, sometimes too powerful.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:01.000
People can really over-rotate on them, and that sometimes creates almost like this.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:09.000
I feel like the chilly climate stuff really comes up for remote teams who are afraid of wasting people's time.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:12.000
There's friction from the tools we need to use to be remote.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:30.000
I think maybe the single biggest thing I would say is just believing as a collective of people that investing and learning together is as important as getting the work done or a very procedural time,

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
but finding a way to do it that really feels authentic.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:39.000
I would probably suggest let's open up the floor to design this together as a team.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:45.000
Maybe we reach out to the team and we say, hey, we're going to have a really—leaders have to do this.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:51.000
It has to be safe, like tell me what's not working about remotes.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:58.000
I've worked with orgs that really have this pluralistic ignorance thing going on where the whole team actually wants to hang out a little bit,

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:08.000
but everybody's afraid of being that person who's asking you to join one more Zoom, so sort of surfacing that conversation together as a team.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:17.000
I've had teams do like a retrospective that's on culture, and then you can—I think you need to diagnose before you fix.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:21.000
So diagnose what about the remote work is pulling you apart.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:25.000
Then you can figure out some specific things to try.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:27.000
Awesome. Thank you so much, Kat.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:28.000
Thank you.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:29.000
Thank you.

